{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514078"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:18:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12267"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12267"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.81,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4789"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77819"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4789"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63340"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"432"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43993"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77819"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the ophthalmology clinic with gradual visual loss which is painless, bilateral and associated with the presence of floaters. He is a non-smoker. He has a medical history of diabetes, myocardial infarction, prior stroke, and hypertension. His last HbA1c was 11%. On examination his blood pressure is 150/100 mmHg, pulse rate 99/min, and temperature 37.2C. His visual acuity is 6/18 with no improvement on pinhole testing. Fundoscopic examination shows retinal oedema, retinal neovascularisation and small vitreous haemorrhages. The intraocular pressure is 17mmHg. The rest of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Background diabetic retinopathy","Pre-proliferative diabetic retinopathy","Proliferative diabetic retinopathy","Advanced diabetic retinopathy","Burnt out retinopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cause of gradual and painless visual loss in this patient is diabetic retinopathy because of classical signs on fundoscopy (retinal oedema, retinal neovascularisation and vitreous haemorrhages) along with a history of uncontrolled diabetes and smoking (risk factors for diabetic retinopathy). Diabetic retinopathy is defined as a non-inflammatory disease of the retina, characterised by progressive dysfunction of the retinal vasculature secondary to hyperglycaemia. Diabetic retinopathy is classified clinically into stages that are in the options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is presenting with \u003Cstrong\u003Eproliferative diabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E which is a relatively advanced level because of the presence of retinal neovascularisation, which is a hallmark of proliferative diabetic retinopathy. Other signs include neovascularisation of the iris, pre-retinal haemorrhage, vitreous haemorrhage and tractional retinal detachment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBackground diabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the initial stage of diabetic retinopathy and is characterised by the presence of microaneurysms, retinal oedema, hard exudates and retinal haemorrhages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPre-proliferative diabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by findings of venous dilatation, cotton wool spots (nerve fibre ischaemia or infarcts), and intraretinal microvascular abnormality on fundoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvanced diabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the next stage of proliferative diabetic retinopathy and is characterised by persistent vitreous haemorrhages, tractional retinal detachment and neovascular glaucoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBurnt-out diabetic retinopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is the last stage of disease progression and it is characterised by regression of vascular components and only fibrous component is left.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The characteristic sign of proliferative diabetic retinopathy is retinal neovascularisation.","Diabetic retinopathy is a progressive condition that can lead to significant vision loss if not managed appropriately."],"references":["Jatoi SM. Retina . In: Clinical Opthalmology text and atlas. 6th ed. Karachi, Sindh: Paramount books ; 2020. p. 191\u20135. (1; vol. 1).","Chaudhary S, Zaveri J, Becker N. Proliferative diabetic retinopathy (PDR). Dis Mon. 2021 May;67(5):101140. doi: 10.1016/j.disamonth.2021.101140. Epub 2021 Feb 3. PMID: 33546872. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33546872/","Pandit S, Ho AC, Yonekawa Y. Recent advances in the management of proliferative diabetic retinopathy. Curr Opin Ophthalmol. 2023 May 1;34(3):232-236. doi: 10.1097/ICU.0000000000000946. Epub 2023 Mar 3. PMID: 36866849. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36866849/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63340"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12267"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63340"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T12:46:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T12:47:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4789"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77819"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/432"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diabetic retinopathy","synonyms":["Diabetic eye disease"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T11:31:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{